    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Afrocominella elongata </i>(hence the common name), also known as Variable Agulhas whelk.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_10429",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Narrowly fusiform medium-sized whelk with a constricted siphonal canal and a high spire that is usually longer than the aperture. Whorls slightly shouldered, sculptured by coarse spiral ridges which become finer above the shoulder. Weak axial ribs running over the spiral ridges create a weakly granular pattern. Colour cream-yellow to brown with axial brown streaks and spots. Aperture brown, operculum yellow. Foot white with mottled-dashed black pattern.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_10430",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": [
                {
                    "text": "",
                    "altText": "",
                    "title": "",
                    "imageUrl": {
                        "1x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-3229-250.webp",
                        "2x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-3229-500.webp",
                        "4x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-3229-1000.webp"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "text": "",
                    "altText": "",
                    "title": "",
                    "imageUrl": {
                        "1x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-3228-250.webp",
                        "2x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-3228-500.webp",
                        "4x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-3228-1000.webp"
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Shell up to 50 mm, rarely 60 mm in length.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_10431",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> False Bay to Transkei, occasionally in low intertidal but usually subtidal to 160 m.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_10432",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Fairly common and shells frequently found in beach drift. Living animals found under rocks and in crevices in low tide pools but more common subtidally. Most often found in spring when it spawns.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_10433",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Whelks are predators, but diet of this species is not specifically studied. The subspecies <i>A. c. capensis </i>is reported to feed on ‘small red worms’.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_10434",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Appears to spawn in austral spring and lays milky white, lens-shaped egg capsules that have a transparent window on top, which serves as an escape hatch for the young. Development unknown.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_10435",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": [
                {
                    "text": "",
                    "altText": "",
                    "title": "",
                    "imageUrl": {
                        "1x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-3227-250.webp",
                        "2x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-3227-500.webp",
                        "4x": "/localcosmos/user_content/content_images/image-3227-1000.webp"
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Two subspecies are recognised and these are treated here as separate entries although officially considered a single species with unresolved taxonomy. <i>A. c. simoniana</i> has a higher, more elongated spire and occurs along the southern Cape coast to the eastern Transkei, with intermediate forms from False Bay to Cape Agulhas. <i>Afrocominella c. capensis </i>is plumper, with a lower spire, and is the Atlantic coast form.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_10436",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
